## Day 2: Navigation & The Linux File System (SOC Perspective) 📂

### 🛠️ Essential Navigation Commands
In the terminal, speed and precision are vital.
- `pwd` (Print Working Directory): Confirms exactly where I am in the filesystem.
- `ls -la`: Lists all files, including hidden ones (starting with `.`), and displays permissions, owners, and file sizes.
- `cd`: Moves between directories to investigate different system areas.

### 🔍 The "Gold Mine": `/var/log`
This is the most critical directory for an analyst. It contains the "history" of the system.
- **`auth.log` / `secure`**: Tracks login attempts. I use this to identify brute-force attacks.
- **`syslog`**: General system messages and errors.

### 🛡️ The "Attack Surface": `/etc`
This directory contains system-wide configuration files. 
- **Security Risk:** If an attacker gains write access to `/etc`, they can create new users in `/etc/passwd` or change service configurations to create backdoors.
